                    <heading>Defence</heading>
                    <p id="PL.DIR.804">
          As assessed at November 2023, Poland’s active armed forces numbered 100,400, comprising an army of 71,350, a navy of 6,150, air force of 15,000, special forces of 3,250 and territorial defence forces of 4,650. There were also 14,300 border guard and paramilitary personnel. Poland became a full member of the 
          <xr pageref="N" ref="NATO.IO">North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)</xr>
           in 1999. At a NATO summit meeting in Warsaw in July 2016 NATO agreed to deploy four multinational battalions to the Baltic states and Poland. Poland’s priorities for 2017-32 are to bolster the armed forces to act as a deterrent to aggression by the Russian Federation, which is regarded by Poland as a significant threat, particularly given the large-scale Russian invasion of Ukraine in February 2022. Under the Homeland Defence Act signed in March, Poland was to increase defence spending from 2.2% of GDP in 2022 to 3.0% in 2023. Poland also intended to increase the strength of the armed forces to 300,000 by 2035. At November 2022 the NATO battlegroup in Poland numbered around 1,033 personnel.
        </p>
